           =20
<a id=3D"definition" class=3D"anchor"></a>
<h4>Definition of a vector</h4>

<p>A vector is an object that has both a <a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org=
/definition/magnitude_vector" class=3D"definition" title=3D"Magnitude of a =
vector definition: The magnitude of a vector is the length of the vector.">=
magnitude</a> and a direction. =20
Geometrically, we can picture a vector as a directed line segment, whose le=
ngth is the magnitude of the vector and with an arrow indicating the direct=
ion. The direction of the vector is from its tail to its head. </p>

<p class=3D"centeredImage"><a id=3D"image:vector" class=3D"anchor"></a><a h=
ref=3D"https://mathinsight.org/image/vector" title=3D"A vector is an object=
 that has a magnitude and a direction"><img class=3D"displayed" src=3D"http=
s://mathinsight.org/media/image/image/vector.png" alt=3D"A vector" width=3D=
"336" height=3D"165"></a></p>

<p>Two vectors are the same if they have the same magnitude and direction. =
 This means that if we take a vector and translate it to a new position (wi=
thout rotating it), then the vector we obtain at the end of this process is=
 the same vector we had in the beginning.</p>

<p>Two examples of vectors are those that represent force and velocity. =20
Both force and velocity are in a particular direction.  The magnitude of th=
e=20
vector would indicate the strength of the force or the speed associated wit=
h the velocity.</p>


<p>We denote vectors using boldface as in $\vc{a}$ or $\vc{b}$.
Especially when writing by hand where one cannot easily write in
boldface, people will sometimes denote vectors using arrows as in $\vec{a}$=
 or
$\vec{b}$, or they use other markings.  We won't need to use arrows here.
We denote the magnitude of the vector $\vc{a}$ by $\|\vc{a}\|$.
When we want to refer to a number and stress that it is not a vector,
we can call the number a <a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/definition/scal=
ar" class=3D"definition" title=3D"Scalar definition: A scalar is a real num=
ber.">scalar</a>.  We will denote scalars=20
with italics, as in $a$ or $b$.</p>


<p>You can explore the concept of the magnitude and direction of a vector u=
sing the below applet.  Note that moving the vector around doesn't change t=
he vector, as the position of the vector doesn't affect the magnitude or th=
e direction.
But if you stretch or turn the vector by moving just its head or its tail, =
the magnitude or direction will change.  (This applet also shows the coordi=
nates of the vector, which you can read about in <a href=3D"https://mathins=
ight.org/vectors_cartesian_coordinates_2d_3d" class=3D"content" title=3D"Ve=
ctors in two- and three-dimensional Cartesian coordinates: A introduction t=
o representing vectors using the standard Cartesian coordinate systems in t=
he plane and in three-dimensional space.">another page</a>.)</p>

<a id=3D"applet:vector_magnitude_direction" class=3D"anchor"></a><section c=
lass=3D"appletbox"><div class=3D"javascriptapplet"><div class=3D"geogebrawe=
bapplet" id=3D"containerAppletVectorMagnitudeDirection01" style=3D"min-widt=
h:649px;min-height:449px"></div></div>
<p><i>The magnitude and direction of a vector.</i> The blue arrow represent=
s a vector $\vc{a}$.  The two defining properties of a vector, magnitude an=
d direction, are illustrated by a red bar and a green arrow, respectively. =
 The length of the red bar is the magnitude $\|\vc{a}\|$ of the vector $\vc=
{a}$.  The green arrow always has length one, but its direction is the dire=
ction of the vector $\vc{a}$.  The one exception is when $\vc{a}$ is the ze=
ro vector (the only vector with zero magnitude), for which the direction is=
 not defined.  You can change either end of $\vc{a}$ by dragging it with yo=
ur mouse.  You can also move $\vc{a}$ by dragging the middle of the vector;=
 however, changing the position of the $\vc{a}$ in this way does not change=
 the vector, as its magnitude and direction remain unchanged.  </p><p><a hr=
ef=3D"https://mathinsight.org/applet/vector_magnitude_direction" title=3D"A=
n illustration of a vector's magnitude and direction" class=3D"applet">More=
 information about applet.</a> </p></section>


<p>There is one important exception to vectors having a direction.  The <a =
href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/zero_vector" class=3D"content" title=3D"The=
 zero vector: The zero vector is the unique vector having zero length.  The=
 direction of the zero vector is undefined.">zero
vector</a>, denoted by a boldface $\vc{0}$, is the vector of zero length.=
=20
Since it has no length, it is not pointing in any particular direction. =20
There is only one vector of zero length, so we can speak of <b>the</b> zero=
 vector.</p>

<a id=3D"operations" class=3D"anchor"></a>
<h4>Operations on vectors</h4>

<p>We can define a number of operations on vectors geometrically without=20
reference to any coordinate system.  Here we define <a href=3D"https://math=
insight.org/vector_introduction#addition">addition</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
mathinsight.org/vector_introduction#subtraction">subtraction</a>, and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://mathinsight.org/vector_introduction#scalarmultiplication">mul=
tiplication by a scalar</a>.  On separate pages, we discuss two different w=
ays to multiply two vectors together: <a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/do=
t_product" class=3D"content" title=3D"The dot product: Introduction to the =
dot product with a focus on its basic geometric properties.">the dot produc=
t</a> and <a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/cross_product" class=3D"conten=
t" title=3D"The cross product: Introduction to the cross product with a foc=
us on its basic properties. Includes an interactive graphic to illustrate t=
hese properties of the cross product.">the cross product</a>.</p>

<a id=3D"addition" class=3D"anchor"></a>
<h5>Addition of vectors</h5>

<p>Given two vectors $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{b}$, we form their sum $\vc{a}+\vc{b=
}$, as follows.=20
We translate the vector $\vc{b}$ until its tail coincides with the head of =
$\vc{a}$.  (Recall such translation does not change a vector.)=20
Then, the directed line segment from the tail of $\vc{a}$ to the head of $\=
vc{b}$ is the vector $\vc{a}+\vc{b}$.</p>

<p class=3D"centeredImage"><a id=3D"image:vector_a_plus_b" class=3D"anchor"=
></a><a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/image/vector_a_plus_b" title=3D"The=
 sum of two vectors is formed by placing the vectors head to tail."><img cl=
ass=3D"displayed" src=3D"https://mathinsight.org/media/image/image/vector_a=
_plus_b.png" alt=3D"The sum of two vectors" width=3D"397" height=3D"114"></=
a></p>

<p>The vector addition is the way forces and velocities combine.  For examp=
le,
if a car is travelling due north at 20 miles per hour and a child in the ba=
ck
seat behind the driver throws an object at 20 miles per hour toward his
sibling who is sitting due east of him, then the velocity of the object
(relative to the ground!) will be in a north-easterly direction.
The velocity vectors form a right triangle, where the total velocity is the
hypotenuse.  Therefore, the total speed of the object (i.e., the magnitude =
of the velocity vector) is $\sqrt{20^2+20^2}=3D20\sqrt{2}$=20
miles per hour relative to the ground.</p>

<p>Addition of vectors satisfies two important properties.</p>
<ol><li><p>The commutative law, which states the order of addition doesn't =
matter:
$$\vc{a}+\vc{b}=3D\vc{b}+\vc{a}.$$
This law is also called the parallelogram law, as illustrated in the below
image.  Two of the edges of the parallelogram define $\vc{a}+\vc{b}$,=20
and the other pair of edges define $\vc{b}+\vc{a}$.  But, both sums are
equal to the same diagonal of the parallelogram.</p>
<p class=3D"centeredImage"><a id=3D"image:vector_parallelogram_law" class=
=3D"anchor"></a><a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/image/vector_parallelogr=
am_law" title=3D"The parallelogram law shows that vector addition is commut=
ative, i.e., is independent of the order of the vectors."><img class=3D"dis=
played" src=3D"https://mathinsight.org/media/image/image/vector_parallelogr=
am_law.png" alt=3D"The parallelogram law, or commutative law, of vector add=
ition" width=3D"397" height=3D"197"></a></p>
</li>
<li><p>The associative law, which states that the sum of three vectors does
not depend on which pair of vectors is added first:
$$(\vc{a}+\vc{b})+\vc{c} =3D \vc{a} + (\vc{b}+\vc{c}).$$</p>
</li>
</ol>

<p>You can explore the properties of vector addition with the following app=
let. (This applet also shows the coordinates of the vectors, which you can =
read about in <a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/vectors_cartesian_coordina=
tes_2d_3d" class=3D"content" title=3D"Vectors in two- and three-dimensional=
 Cartesian coordinates: A introduction to representing vectors using the st=
andard Cartesian coordinate systems in the plane and in three-dimensional s=
pace.">another page</a>.)</p>

<a id=3D"applet:vector_sum" class=3D"anchor"></a><section class=3D"appletbo=
x"><div class=3D"javascriptapplet"><div class=3D"geogebrawebapplet" id=3D"c=
ontainerAppletVectorSum02" style=3D"min-width:650px;min-height:439px"></div=
></div>
<p><i>The sum of two vectors.</i> The sum $\vc{a}+\vc{b}$ of the vector $\v=
c{a}$ (blue arrow) and the vector $\vc{b}$ (red arrow) is shown by the gree=
n arrow.  As vectors are independent of their starting position, both blue =
arrows represent the same vector $\vc{a}$ and both red arrows represent the=
 same vector $\vc{b}$.  The sum $\vc{a}+\vc{b}$ can be formed by placing th=
e tail of the vector $\vc{b}$ at the head of the vector $\vc{a}$.  Equivale=
ntly, it can be formed by placing the tail of the vector $\vc{a}$ at the he=
ad of the vector $\vc{b}$.  Both constructions together form a parallelogra=
m, with the sum $\vc{a}+\vc{b}$ being a diagonal.  (For this reason, the co=
mmutative law $\vc{a}+\vc{b}=3D\vc{b}+\vc{a}$ is sometimes called the paral=
lelogram law.)  You can change $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{b}$ by dragging the yellow=
 points.</p><p><a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/applet/vector_sum" title=
=3D"Geometric representation of the sum of two vectors" class=3D"applet">Mo=
re information about applet.</a> </p></section>

<a id=3D"subtraction" class=3D"anchor"></a>
<h5>Vector subtraction</h5>

<p>Before we define subtraction, we define the vector $-\vc{a}$, which=20
is the opposite of $\vc{a}$.  The vector $-\vc{a}$ is the vector=20
with the same magnitude as $\vc{a}$ but that is pointed in the opposite dir=
ection.</p>

<p class=3D"centeredImage"><a id=3D"image:vector_opposite" class=3D"anchor"=
></a><a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/image/vector_opposite" title=3D"The=
 vector that is opposite to a given vector has the same magnitude but the o=
pposite direction."><img class=3D"displayed" src=3D"https://mathinsight.org=
/media/image/image/vector_opposite.png" alt=3D"The opposite vector" width=
=3D"423" height=3D"164"></a></p>

<p>We define subtraction as addition with the opposite of a vector:
$$\vc{b}-\vc{a} =3D \vc{b} + (-\vc{a}).$$
This is equivalent to turning vector $\vc{a}$ around in the applying the
above rules for addition.  Can you see how the vector $\vc{x}$ in the
below figure is equal to $\vc{b}-\vc{a}$?  Notice how this is the same
as stating that $\vc{a}+\vc{x}=3D\vc{b}$, just like with subtraction of
scalar numbers.</p>

<p class=3D"centeredImage"><a id=3D"image:vector_b_minus_a" class=3D"anchor=
"></a><a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/image/vector_b_minus_a" title=3D"T=
he difference of two vectors is formed by placing the tails of two vectors =
together."><img class=3D"displayed" src=3D"https://mathinsight.org/media/im=
age/image/vector_b_minus_a.png" alt=3D"The difference of two vectors" width=
=3D"407" height=3D"100"></a></p>


<a id=3D"scalarmultiplication" class=3D"anchor"></a>
<h5>Scalar multiplication</h5>

<p>Given a vector $\vc{a}$ and a real number (<a href=3D"https://mathinsigh=
t.org/definition/scalar" class=3D"definition" title=3D"Scalar definition: A=
 scalar is a real number.">scalar</a>) $\lambda$, we can form the vector $\=
lambda\vc{a}$ as follows.
If $\lambda$ is positive, then $\lambda\vc{a}$ is the vector whose directio=
n is the same as the direction of $\vc{a}$ and whose length is $\lambda$ ti=
mes the length of $\vc{a}$.
In this case, multiplication by $\lambda$ simply stretches (if $\lambda&gt;=
1$) or
compresses (if $0 &lt; \lambda &lt;1$) the vector $\vc{a}$.</p>

<p>If, on the other hand, $\lambda$ is negative, then we have to take the=
=20
opposite of $\vc{a}$ before stretching or compressing it.  In other words,=
=20
the vector $\lambda\vc{a}$ points in the opposite direction of $\vc{a}$,
and the length of $\lambda\vc{a}$ is $|\lambda|$ times the length of $\vc{a=
}$.
No matter the sign of $\lambda$, we observe that the magnitude of $\lambda\=
vc{a}$ is $|\lambda|$ times the magnitude of $\vc{a}$: $\| \lambda \vc{a}\|=
 =3D |\lambda| \|\vc{a}\|$.
</p>

<p>Scalar multiplications satisfies many of the same properties as=20
the usual multiplication.</p>
<ol>
  <li>$s(\vc{a}+\vc{b}) =3D s\vc{a} + s\vc{b}$  (distributive law, form 1)<=
/li>
  <li>$(s+t)\vc{a} =3D s\vc{a}+t\vc{a}$ (distributive law, form 2)</li>
  <li>$1\vc{a} =3D \vc{a}$</li>
  <li>$(-1)\vc{a} =3D -\vc{a}$</li>
  <li>$0\vc{a} =3D \vc{0}$</li>
</ol>

<p>In the last formula, the zero on the left is the number 0, while the
zero on the right is the vector $\vc{0}$, which is the unique vector whose =
length is zero.</p>

<p>If $\vc{a} =3D \lambda\vc{b}$ for some scalar $\lambda$, then we say
that the vectors $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{b}$ are parallel.  If $\lambda$ is negat=
ive,
some people say that $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{b}$ are anti-parallel, but we will
not use that language.</p>

<p>We were able to describe vectors, vector addition, vector subtraction, a=
nd
scalar multiplication without reference to any coordinate system. =20
The advantage of such purely geometric reasoning is that our results hold g=
enerally, independent of any coordinate system in which the vectors live.
However, sometimes it is useful to express vectors in terms of coordinates,
as discussed in a page about  <a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/vectors_ca=
rtesian_coordinates_2d_3d" class=3D"content" title=3D"Vectors in two- and t=
hree-dimensional Cartesian coordinates: A introduction to representing vect=
ors using the standard Cartesian coordinate systems in the plane and in thr=
ee-dimensional space.">vectors in the standard Cartesian coordinate systems=
</a> in the plane and in three-dimensional space.</p>

